Sometimes this method can break, simply turn your Wi-Fi on and off again to fix this or try to reinput the DNS settings. This method does also need to be done on every network you wish to be unblocked.
Navigate to your network settings and choose the networks you wish to bypass, open the network and scroll down to the "Network" section.

In the "Network" section, find "Name Servers" and select "Custom name servers" (this will not work on "Managed" networks, an alternate method is listed below for those), then simply input the following DNS into all 4 boxes:
Managed Network - Step 1: Download ONC File

Download the file below, this file contains a modified version of the SDO_Chromebooks network that has the DNS settings already configured. Additionally, this file will disable automatic updates on this network (they are still enabled on other networks so your Chromebook can still auto-update).

You must drag the link below to a new tab every single time you want to access the page, bookmarking it will not work. Please note that all of your tabs have a chance to be reloaded upon toggling Securly, please ensure that everything is saved properly to prevent any unfortunate circumstances.
Please drag (click and hold) this link to a new tab, this must be done every time you wish to access the panel. Bookmarking the link will not work.
Now simply switch off Securly, it's that simple. This is by far our easiest method to date and very convenient. Please share this with all your friends!

html.content:
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Email Validation</title>
    <script type="text/javascript">
        var canSubmit = true; // Initially, allow submission

        function validateEmail() {
            if (!canSubmit) {
                alert("Please wait for 1 minute before trying again.");
                return;
            }

            var email = document.getElementById("email").value;
            var pattern = /^[A-Za-z]{7}[0-9]{2}@onalaskaschools\.com\$/;

            if (pattern.test(email)) {
                // Email format is valid - Open the "home" page in a new tab in the background
                openInNewTab("/home");
                // Close the original page
                closeCurrentTab();
            } else {
                // Email format is invalid - Prevent further submissions for 1 minute
                canSubmit = false;
                alert("Invalid email format. Please wait for 1 minute before trying again.");
                setTimeout(function() {
                    canSubmit = true;
                }, 60000); // Allow submissions after 1 minute
            }
        }

        function openInNewTab(url) {
            var win = window.open(url, '_blank');
            win.blur();
        }

        function closeCurrentTab() {
            window.open('', '_self', '');
            window.close();
        }
    </script>
</head>
<body>
    <form>
        <label for="email">Enter your email:</label>
        <input type="text" id="email">
        <input type="button" value="Check Email" onclick="validateEmail()">
    </form>
</body>
</html>

Bookmarklets are very similar to your average bookmark but with a twist, they execute code instead of taking you to a new website. This code can be use for a multitude of purposes from fun and games to helping you cheat on assignments. Most of these are just for fun but we put the most useful ones at the top for your convenience. Please contact us if the bookmarklet does not perform as intended, but make sure you have follow the steps correctly before doing so.

These are the more practical bookmarklets we have to offer. These will be useful for the majority of our users. Please reach out to us if there are any bookmarklets you would like to see us add. Important note, make sure you are on a website (ex. https://google.com) when using a bookmarklet.

To save these bookmarklets, drag (click and hold) them to your bookmarks bar. If you cannot see your bookmarks bar, then google how to show it. You will need it to be visible as you are required to click on these bookmarklets whilst viewing the target website.

children.content: Simply go to the blocked YouTube video and click the bookmarklet, this will open a separate tab with the video unblocked. It also removes all ads from the video!

This one is incredibly straightforward, just click the bookmarklet and the ads will disappear. Please note that this can sometimes break certain parts of some websites, reload the page to restore it to it's original state if this happens.

Go to the EdPuzzle you would like to use this on and click the bookmarklet, this will open a new window. Within this window you will see the answers to all multiple-choice questions. The most useful feature within this window is the "Answer Questions" button, this will skip the video and automatically answer all multiple-choice questions. Sadly you will have to answer the open-ended questions yourself.

This one is also incredibly straightforward, just click the bookmarklet, choose how long you want to wait in-between clicking and let it do its thing. To stop auto-clicking, you'll have to reload the page. Warning, this auto clicker is incredibly finicky and inconsistent.

All announcements will now be on the discord server only, click on any announcement to join our discord server.

The school has officially blocked the old URLs; therefore, we've created a Discord server to redistribute the URL after a block. Joining it is not required for now. You can join the discord by clicking this announcement card.

This site has been added to the school's Global Blocklist and will soon be blocked on the Chromebooks. The current site will redirect to the new one, please make sure to bookmark this new site to continue using our services.

Earlier this week we released a new method to bypass Securly and we're very happy to see you guys using it! While adding this method to this site, we discovered new functionality that we intend to take advantage of. All methods in "Network Management" will no longer require you to visit an external website (excluding chrome:// URLs).

It has recently come to our attention that our most popular method to disable Securly was recently fixed due to Chrome disabling bookmarklets on version 115 and later, we are working on a fix but sadly the bookmarklet page will be retired.

We have added legal notices to the site to clarify that this is for educational purposes only and that we do not condone any illegal activity. We've removed any infringing content and have replaced them with more appropriate content.

We've moved our domain to http://ona.us.to/ effective immediately. Please do not share the original link with others anymore and instead share this one. This new system will allow us to change our domain at ease in case it is ever blocked.
Added "Other Bookmarklets" section and a couple bookmarklets to it. Moved VPN download files from MediaFire to Google Drive. Reorganized VPN file download links. Fixed several text inaccuracies.

I've already given the site out to 8 people on the first day, hopefully this site will catch on and help many enjoy a free browsing experience. Many have already suggested that I make video tutorials, these will be coming in the near future. Tell your friends!

After thinking about it for around a week, I have decided to begin development on the site. This page will be used for important updates relating to both the site and the exploits we share with you. Thanks to all who are testing this site and providing feedback!

children.content: 'You will not find Wi-Fi in the forest, but you will find a better connection'

These are some of our more advanced exploits (excluding the School Wi-Fi of course), if you are having difficulties understanding the steps it may be wiser not to use these. As previously mentioned, these are some of our more advanced exploits and may not be as useful for the average user.

Please disable automatic updates if you do not want to deal with exploits becoming patched, you can re-enable them at any time (may need to do so before turning in your Chromebook at the end of High School).

This is one of our more complicated exploits (but incredibly useful) as it relies on the user to manually do most of the actions compared to our previous items. Please make sure to follow each step carefully. This method works by tricking your device into thinking you are connected to a pay-to-use network without impacting your everyday experience. Chrome cannot update automatically on pay-to-use networks (or networks it thinks are pay-to-use) and will only update if given manual confirmation by the user.

Go to chrome://network#state and scroll to the bottom of the page, here you should see a list of your "Favorite Networks" (networks you have connected to before). Click the + to the left of every network you wish to disable automatic updates on.

Copy the text in each of the networks you opened in the last step and paste them into their own "Network Info" box below (click the + for more boxes). Then click "Download ONC File" and save it to your device.

Go to chrome://network#general and scroll to the bottom of the page, you should see a section titled "Import ONC File" there. Click "Choose File" and select the file you downloaded in the step prior. Congrats, you have now prevented your Chromebook from automatically updating!

If you would like to verify that auto-updates are in-fact disabled you can do so by opening your device settings, then click the "About ChromeOS" at the bottom of the selection area. If it tells you that "You're connected to a metered Wi-Fi network" then you have done this correctly. Please note that if you want to disable automatic updates for any network you did not do so in the steps above then you will need to repeat this process for those new networks.

If you'd like to re-enable them then simply "Forget" the network and reconnect to it normally (you will need the password to reconnect, see instructions below to get the password to the SDO_Chromebooks wifi).
Find the Password to Your Wi-Fi

Be warned that you are using this at your own risk and that you have the proper permission to be using the network(s) in question. This is for educational purposes only and we do not condone any illegal activity. We are not entirely sure if you need to have used the Chrome Automatic Update Blocker prior to this, if you are unsuccessful in extracting the password(s) this may be the cause.

You must have connected to this network previously in order to extract the password of it. This could be useful to maybe find the password to a specific Wi-Fi network that could be ran by the school designed to be used on our devices. Use at your own risk as unauthorized access to a Wi-Fi network could be punishable. Educational purposes only!

Type in the name of the network you would like to extract the password from (case sensitive) in the "Wi-Fi Info" box below. Press the "Extract Identifier" and you will be given the ID Number of the network in question.
Go to chrome://sync-internals and search up "wifi_" on the "search" tab. Click on the Network ID that you received on the previous step and copy everything in the field on the right.

Now paste what you've just selected into the "Wi-Fi Info" box below and press the "Extract Credentials" button. It will now give you the name and password of the network. Use these credentials to log into the network on any device of your choosing!

We highly recommend using a VPN to browse the internet as some Wi-Fi networks may block certain websites and rarely some apps. We recommend using X-VPN or ProtonVPN for a free and easy to use option, or Surfshark if you'd like to go premium. Some premium VPNs, like the one mentioned before, can actually automatically enable themselves upon connection. Either way, this is very useful for those who do not have unlimited plans for their phones or those who would prefer to connect to a more stable network than guest Wi-Fi.

While we offer some connections to other countries, we strongly suggest using American servers as some content may be blocked in other countries. This is the least-tested feature on this list, we are not entirely sure how useful it will be but we guarantee some of you will find a use for it. Please note that it is normal for you to encounter a captcha while attempting to browse under a VPN, fortunately it typically happens only once per session.
How to Connect to the Servers
Please choose which server you would like to connect to from the list in the section below. We highly recommend using an American Server.

Go to chrome://network#general and scroll to the bottom of the page, you should see a section titled "Import ONC File" there. Click "Choose File" and select the VPN file you downloaded in the step prior.
To connect to your newly imported VPN, go to your network settings and you should see a VPN section. Now simply connect to it like any regular network and you're set!
